<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Stockport Homes</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Stockport Homes </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Changes of which consultation will consider the effects:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local Housing Allowance reforms</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Direct payment of housing costs to claimants</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Household benefit cap</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Social sector size criteria</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Localised council tax support</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Committee is particularly interested in hearing views on:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">New and innovate responses to changes to housing support already taking place</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Implications of changes for:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Landlords</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Local authorities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Claimants, particularly those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in vulnerable groups, and those in supported and temporary accommodation</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Treatment of housing costs within Universal Credit</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Key points</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> from Temporary Accommodation perspective</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Direct payments</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TA staff currently provide extensive support for customers in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">claiming housing costs via Housing Benefit to ensure income is secured, which includes maintaining a good working relationship with the council’s Revenues and Benefits department. This relationship is not likely to be possible as support for housing costs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">move under the DWP, especially where the customer is hard to engage and has not given consent to discuss their application. This may lead to delays in rental costs being paid</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As customers will be expected to take control of their own household finances und</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er Universal Credit, there is a risk that they may not also take responsibility for notifying the DWP of their change in circumstances when they move into TA – unless consent is given to TA staff. This could lead to delays in payment adjustments to include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> updated housing costs</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Monthly payments to customers could pose several issues for TA, including:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where customers are rehoused quickly or part-way through the month, and support for housing costs have not yet been paid. TA rents are calculated on a weekly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">basis and this could therefore lead to loss of income</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where certain customer groups, particularly offenders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, leave TA schemes unexpectedly, monthly support for housing costs may not yet have been processed – but at least one week’s rental income may have b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">een missed</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Several customer groups, including those leaving prison or hospitals, may not have Universal Credit claims in place upon entering TA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; this could exacerbate the above issues around delays or non-payment of housing costs. Consideration will need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to be given as to whether claims can be backdated as per current arrangements</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TA residents are some of the most hard to reach chaotic customers within any given borough and are often experiencing substance dependency and as such very often have large debts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with loan sharks and ‘dealers’ – it can be foreseen that direct payments of such large sums of money to those who have never budgeted before and have more ‘pressing’ debts, will be paid to other sources than a landlord. Ultimately this will lead to large </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arrears, affecting any future rehousing and eviction from homeless accommodation, increasing rough sleeper numbers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Similarly, many people who reside in temporary accommodation have lost their previous properties due to rent arrears – these could be social</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or private housing tenants, who have often had HB in payment direct to a landlord, yet have failed to pay a shortfall or a minimal service charge which has eventually amassed a large debt. Direct payments of such large amounts of money intended for househ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">old costs are unlikely to be paid by the claimant to the landlord where such customers have failed to pay even minimal service charge fees to previous landlords. Again, this would result in eviction after the first month payment was missed, and lead to inc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reased rough sleeper numbers and increased input from Social Care to accommodate children, where families were being evicted.    </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It has been outlined that deductions, including sanctions and income above the benefit cap or from earnings of those in low-pa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">id employment, will be taken from the support for housing costs element of Universal Credit. There have already been difficulties in securing service charge payments from customers in TA who have had existing benefits sanctioned; this is likely to be exace</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rbated as more substantial deductions come into place</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although exemptions to direct payment have been outlined, these need to be clarified. The qualifying period of 8 weeks non-payment before direct payments can be requested also poses a particular issue f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or TA due to the transient nature of its customers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> TA could not keep a household beyond one month’s missed payment due to the levels of arrears built up – the service could not afford to run like this. After one missed payment, people would be evicted. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Other issues: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Claimant Commitment</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This could pose particular issues for homeless people. Current information from Universal Credit pilot areas suggests that the commitment will involve customers devoting 30+ hours per week to job searches, or risk sanction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s. This time commitment could be problematic for a population already having to deal with associated issues around their homelessness, without a settled base. Not meeting the commitment and resultant sanctions could have serious implications for rental inc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ome at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">TA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As above, if sanctioned UC meant no housing costs are paid to cover rent, this would result in eviction. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“Digital by default” also presents an issue for those in TA, due to limited access to ICT facilities. Whilst some provision is available wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thin the schemes and local area, resources are limited especially when competing with others in a similar situatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In addition, it cannot be stressed enough the high level needs and vulnerability that comes with this client group – often a lack of any fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rmal education; learning difficulties; mental and physical health issues; drug and alcohol dependency issues </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etc.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will prevent this client group from being able to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">engage with any digital inclusion initiatives, and as such will present major problems in te</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rms of them being able to use ICT facilities or engage with support staff attempting to support them in doing so. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Other issues: Household benefit cap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, social sector size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and TA</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The definition of ‘exempt supported accommodation’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">too</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> narrow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reflect the actual circumstances of many homeless customers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, as is the DWP statement that the majority of households in TA are in accommodation procured from the private sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Under homelessness legislation, local authorities can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> several types of acc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ommodation which is not limited to those falling within the definition of exempt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Stockport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> almost all homeless customers are placed into accommodation managed by the ALMO on behalf of the Metropolitan Borough Council; therefore these customers, over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">30</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> households (families and single occupants)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> per year, face being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adversely affected by reforms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> despite this accommodation provi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ding the same</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to vulnerable customers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as defined </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exempt supported accommodation scheme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Temporary Accommodation in Stoc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">kport provides high level intensive suppo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rt, as defined in SEA criteria.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Evidence from the Universal Credit Pathfinders has also caused further concern with regards to ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exempt supported accommodation’. One Pathfinder has reported that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">there is some confusi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on with regards to how the exemption is applied, as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a DWP representative issued advice stating that for existing Universal Credit claimants, moving in to TA / exempt supported accom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">modation would be classed as a “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">change of circumstances” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the exemption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for supported housing costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would not apply as it would with current legacy benefits. A significant proportion of TA resident intakes will require a “change of circumstances”; therefore this presents a real risk to rental income as well as posing a confusing scenario to vulnerable h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">omeless clients. Therefore there needs to be clarification and a uniform definition of what is classed as exempt, and how this comes to be applied from the DWP.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The basis of entitlement to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">temporary accommodation costs in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Universal Credit on household size</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rather than accommodation type does not take into account the demand, throughput and pressure on TA.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is also exacerbated by the benefit cap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> already in place</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Customers are placed into TA overwhelmingly on an emergency basis, and into whichever flat/r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oom vacancy is available. Due to TA schemes often being at capacity and the broad range of households within them, there is not always scope to move customers into more suitably sized accommodation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Even where a move is possible there is a risk that some f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lats, e.g. larger units carrying higher rent, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under-occupied </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">due to the on-going need to provide some form of accommodation to homeless households</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and further reduce rental income. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The inflexibility posed by these size criteria therefore has serio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">us consequences for both rental income at TA, and financial pressure on customers who may n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eed to meet shortfalls in rent.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">1 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>